      "Someone bought 30 WordPress plugins and planted a backdoor in all of them tops HN at 838 pts (235 comments, 0.28:1 comment-to-point ratio) — the day's highest-scoring story and the supply chain attack the open-source registry model has been designed to enable. The post at anchor.host/someone-bought-30-wordpress-plugins-and-planted-a-backdoor-in-all-of-them documents a structural attack: a trusted plugin author's commit access was acquired by a new owner on WordPress.org, who injected PHP deserialization backdoors across 30 active plugins on April 6, 2026, in a 6-hour 44-minute window. The payload sat dormant for eight months in version 2.6.7, disguised as a WordPress compatibility changelog entry. The 0.28:1 ratio is the practitioner community performing forensic analysis, not debate: 235 engineers cataloguing what was missed, what controls were absent, and what the attack surface of trust-by-author looks like at registry scale. WordPress.org has no mechanism to flag plugin ownership transfers, no change-of-control notification to users, and no additional code review triggered when a new committer pushes to a high-install-count plugin. The eight-month dormancy window is the attack's architectural insight: a backdoor that sleeps for eight months after acquisition evades every install-time security scan and dependency audit because no scanner has reason to re-examine a previously trusted, previously stable codebase. The community consensus in the thread is precise: trust stored in author identity rather than code provenance is a structural liability when author identity can be purchased. Every open-source registry — npm, PyPI, RubyGems, crates.io, WordPress.org — uses this same trust model: the author is verified; the code review is optional; the ownership transfer is invisible. The 30-plugin attack is a proof-of-concept that this model fails at the point of acquisition, and the failure is silent for as long as the attacker chooses to wait.",
